05040nam a22006855i 9780226451787DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20172017ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a2016041541  a9780226451787  a(DE-B1597)524267  a(OCoLC)979417534  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL00aML3479b.R63 2017 4aML3479b.R63 2017 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a781.64089/960732231 aRoberts, Brian, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBlackface Nation :bRace, Reform, and Identity in American Popular Music, 1812-1925 /cBrian Roberts. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (384 p.) :b16 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Carnival -- t2. The Vulgar Republic -- t3. Jim Crow’s Genuine Audience -- t4. Black Song -- t5. Meet the Hutchinsons -- t6. Love Crimes -- t7. The Middle-Class Moment -- t8. Culture Wars -- t9. Black America -- t10. Conclusion: Musical without End -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs the United States transitioned from a rural nation to an urbanized, industrial giant between the War of 1812 and the early twentieth century, ordinary people struggled over the question of what it meant to be American. As Brian Roberts shows in Blackface Nation, this struggle is especially evident in popular culture and the interplay between two specific strains of music: middle-class folk and blackface minstrelsy. The Hutchinson Family Singers, the Northeast’s most popular middle-class singing group during the mid-nineteenth century, is perhaps the best example of the first strain of music. The group’s songs expressed an American identity rooted in communal values, with lyrics focusing on abolition, women’s rights, and socialism. Blackface minstrelsy, on the other hand, emerged out of an audience-based coalition of Northern business elites, Southern slaveholders, and young, white, working-class men, for whom blackface expressed an identity rooted in individual self-expression, anti-intellectualism, and white superiority. Its performers embodied the love-crime version of racism, in which vast swaths of the white public adored African Americans who fit blackface stereotypes even as they used those stereotypes to rationalize white supremacy. By the early twentieth century, the blackface version of the American identity had become a part of America’s consumer culture while the Hutchinsons’ songs were increasingly regarded as old-fashioned. Blackface Nation elucidates the central irony in America’s musical history: much of the music that has been interpreted as black, authentic, and expressive was invented, performed, and enjoyed by people who believed strongly in white superiority. At the same time, the music often depicted as white, repressed, and boringly bourgeois was often socially and racially inclusive, committed to reform, and devoted to challenging the immoralities at the heart of America’s capitalist order.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aAfrican AmericansxMusicxHistory and criticism. 0aMinstrel musiczUnited StatesxHistory and criticism. 0aMusic and racezUnited StatesxHistory. 0aPopular music - United States - 19th century - History and criticism. 0aPopular musiczUnited Statesy19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aPopular musiczUnited Statesy20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aAfrican Americans.  aHutchinson Family Singers.  aNineteenth Century.  aUnited States History.  aabolitionism.  ablackface mMinstrelsy.  anational identity.  apatriotism.  apopular culture.  apopular music.  aracism.